areas from Scotland to Switzerland and the Spanish Atlantic World. By bringing such a diverse set of localised studies into concert for the first time, this volume exposes the many intersections and tensions that arose between and within communities as they attempted to translate the ideal of charity into practice. This comparative approach shifts the focus from binary definitions of ‘deserving’ and ‘undeserving’ poor or ‘Catholic’ and ‘Protestant’. Instead, Do good unto all charts a new course for the study of charity beyond institutional poor relief, where the matrix of individual ideas and experiences can be fully appreciated.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCharitieszEuropexHistory. 0aCharityxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aPublic welfarezEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh  aCalvinism.  aCatholicism.  aLutheranism.  abeggars.  aconsistory.  adeacons.  apiety.  apilgrimage.  apoverty.  avagrancy.1 aB. Thomley, Jared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBall, Rachael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aC. Howard, Kristen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChung-Kim, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aE. Salamanca, Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehler, Timothy G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aG. Fehler, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJ. Gray, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJ. Hartman, Abigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJack, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomley,